# HTML Story Extraction Guide

When the user provides an HTML prototype, this guide explains how to read it for everything you need to build the video. The HTML is a **data source and state map** — not a visual template to reproduce.

---

## Why you extract, not replicate

| Replicating the HTML | Extracting the story |
|---------------------|---------------------|
| Full app chrome (nav, sidebar, breadcrumbs) | Only the 3–5 elements that prove the value |
| Every form field | 2–3 most illustrative fields, pre-filled |
| Real browser font sizes (13–15px) | ~1.5× larger (floating on a 1080p canvas) |
| App-level information density | Marketing-level clarity |
| "What the product looks like" | "What makes the product worth watching" |

---

## Step 1 — Extract the State Machine

The most important thing to extract from the HTML is the **state machine** — what states the feature goes through, in what order, triggered by what events.

### What to look for

Scan for:
- **Badge / status values** — e.g. `pending`, `validated`, `active`, `incident`, `paid`, `expired`. These become the animation beats.
- **Status labels** in the HTML text — exact strings you'll use verbatim in Badge components
- **Conditional visibility** — classes like `hidden`, `d-none`, or style switches — these reveal which states can coexist or replace each other
- **Color coding** — which status maps to which color (success green, error red, warning yellow, muted grey)

### Output: State Machine Map

Write this before building anything:

```
States (in order): En attente → Validée → Paiement reçu → Incident
Triggers: user validates card → first payment collected → payment fails
Key moment: Incident — this is the "value moment" (the system catches it)
Badge types: pending | validated | paid | incident | failed | scheduled | expired
```

---

## Step 2 — Extract Real Data (verbatim)

Use actual values from the HTML. Real numbers make the product feel live and trustworthy. Never invent placeholder data.

### What to look for

```html
<!-- KPI stat cards -->
<div class="stat">
  <span class="value">38</span>
  <span class="label">Plans actifs</span>
  <span class="sub">En cours de remboursement</span>
</div>

<!-- Table rows — extract 4–6 representative rows -->
<tr>
  <td>Karim Benali</td>
  <td>CTR-2025-0112</td>
  <td>450 €</td>
  <td class="badge badge-incident">Incident</td>
</tr>

<!-- Form fields — note labels and example values -->
<label>Nombre d'échéances</label>
<input type="number" value="3" placeholder="Ex: 3">

<!-- Business logic in tooltips, help text, or aria labels -->
<span title="Montant divisé par le nombre d'échéances">150 € / mois</span>
```

### Output: Data Inventory

```ts
// In your T object (const T = {...}) — keep the inline approach, no separate file
// Map HTML CSS variables to Piloc tokens:
// --color-primary → T.navy (#0E1029)
// --color-accent  → T.mist (#9DB8EE)
// --color-success → T.success (#329547)
// --color-error   → T.error (#ec6369)
// --color-warning → T.warning (#ffb704)

// KPI data array (module level, before components)
const KPI_DATA = [
  { label: "Non validées",  value: 14,    sub: "En attente de consentement", color: T.warning },
  { label: "En cours",      value: 38,    sub: "Plan actif",                 color: T.info    },
  { label: "Avec incident", value: 5,     sub: "Échéance(s) échouée(s)",     color: T.error   },
  { label: "À encaisser",   value: 12840, sub: "Sur 57 demandes actives",    color: T.text    },
];

// Table row data (extract 4–6 rows — enough to feel like a real table, not overwhelming)
const ROWS = [
  { name: "Karim Benali", contract: "CTR-2025-0112", amount: "450 €",
    status: "validated", statusLabel: "Validée",
    collected: "150 €", total: "450 €", progress: 33, barColor: T.mist,
    honored: "1 / 3", incident: "Fonds insuf.", incidentType: "incident" },
  // ... extract verbatim from HTML
];
```

